Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and their son Dushko cast their vote for the Macedonian referendum on changing the name of the country that would pave the way for their accession to the European Union in Strumica, Macedonia, on 30 September 2018.
In front of parliament in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov prepared a small stage and put up chairs in front of tents set up for those who boycotted the referendum.
“We are in favour of joining NATO and the EU, but we want to do so with our heads held high and not through the service door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don’t accept us as Macedonia, we can go to other countries like China and Russia and join the Eurasian Union.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20 percent.
“I think the vast majority will be in favour because more than 80 percent of our citizens are in favour of joining the EU and NATO,” Zaev said.
He said a positive outcome would be the “confirmation of our future.”
A poll published last Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Political Research revealed that between 30 and 43 percent of voters would participate in the referendum, a figure that is below the required number.
Another poll conducted by the Macedonian television network Telma indicated that 57 percent of those polled planned to go to vote on Sunday.
