While Ri resumed well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to "gradual" denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded as it took action, his statement seemed important, as it did not reject unilateral denuclearization as had happened with Pyongyang in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to “denuclearize” the Korean peninsula while Trump ensured North Korea’s security.
North Korea has long sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has declared that Pyongyang must first lay down its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted easing tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its objective of coercive action, and even opposes the ‘declaration of the end of the war’,” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can make us kneel is an impossible dream for those who don’t know us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions aggravate our distrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that the US leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
However, he spoke of three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If the other part of this denuclearization issue were South Korea and not the United States, denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to a standstill."
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly it was inevitable to strike the United States with North Korean missiles after “evil president” Trump called Kim “rocket man on a suicide mission.”
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said there is still a lot of work to be done and that sanctions must be maintained until North Korea denuclearizes.
Trump said Wednesday that there was no deadline for that, and that “it takes two years, three or five months anyway.”
China and Russia are discussing whether the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures it has taken.
