National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
New research is being carried out on a farm in the Scottish Highlands to reveal how bats use the landscape to hunt for food.
The results are expected to shed light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
This study led by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow the bats Pipistrellus pygmaeus and Pipistrellus pipistrellus, as well as the bats Myotis daubentonii and Plecotus auritus in the Inverewe gardens at Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed at key locations around the property to keep track of bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys with manual detectors.
An expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat calls and what each species is doing.
Then, a habitat map will be drawn up to create a detailed landscape-scale image of your behavior.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor at NTS, hopes the results will show which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creating grasslands and what is the best way to maintain forests for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined considerably in the last century.
These animals are threatened by construction and development work affecting children and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting also pose a risk, as do flies’ glue traps, some chemical treatments of building materials, and attacks by domestic cats.
The bats are not blind.
But because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to hunting.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to locate insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who periodically carry out surveys, inspections of children and, on occasion, even rescues.
The organisation even has Scotland's only and first reserve of bats at Threat Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, Estate Manager, says this is the ideal territory for them.
“Threave has a large area for bats,” he says.
"We have old buildings, historic trees and a great habitat.
But there are a lot of things we don’t yet know about bats, so the work we’ve done here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
It stresses the importance of controlling the presence of bats before performing maintenance tasks on the properties, since it is possible that the involuntary destruction of a single maternity nest could kill up to 400 females and offspring, which could exterminate an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or harass them, as well as destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official with the Bat Conservation Trust, encourages people to help:
“There is still a lot to learn about bats, and for many of the species, we don’t know how their populations are doing.”
