Red tide information: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to the most recent report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission, there is an overall reduction in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Commission, increasingly unequal outcropping conditions are being observed in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier Counties, which may mean that concentrations are decreasing.
The red tide extends approximately 210 km from the coast from the northern counties of Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
Concentrations of 16 km can be found off the coast of Hillsboroug County, but in fewer places compared to last week.
The red tide was also found in Pasco County.
There have been reports of mid-level concentrations on or off the coast of Pinellas County last week, background and elevated concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background and elevated concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County, background and mid-level concentrations on Charlotte County, background and elevated concentrations on or off the coast.
In Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier counties, it is reported that respiratory irritation continues to occur.
No such cases have been reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
